  "prompt": "Is the activity of money laundering prohibited?",
  "response": "Yes, the activity of money laundering is generally prohibited in most jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (dirty money) appear legal (clean money). It typically involves three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing illegal funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Concealing the origins of the funds through complex transactions.\n3. **Integration**: Making the funds appear legitimate by integrating them into the economy.\n\nMoney laundering is illegal because it facilitates criminal activities by allowing criminals to profit from their crimes and integrate these profits into the legitimate economy. This undermines the integrity of financial systems and can have broader socio-economic impacts.\n\nVarious international and national laws have been enacted to combat money laundering. For example:\n\n- The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n- The **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** in the United States requires financial institutions to report certain transactions to help detect and prevent money laundering.\n- The **European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives** provide a framework for EU member states to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment. Financial institutions and businesses are also required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) programs and conduct due diligence to prevent and detect suspicious activities.",
